    <text>
        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Summit&#44; N.J.<lb/>
                Aug. 19&#44; 1885<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Mr. Morais&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>Could you possibly grant<lb/> the writer of the enclosed letter a line<lb/> or two of introduction to M. V&#233;n&#233;zi&#45;<lb/>ani&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>Most respectfully yours<lb/>
                M. Heilprin<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p><del>St. Louis</del> New York August 18<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 85<lb/></p>
                
            <p>Mr M. Heilprin Summit N.J.<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Sir&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p>As you know I came<lb/> to this country <del>orly</del> only for<lb/> the <sic>purpos</sic> to devote myself<lb/> to the agriculture and in<lb/> consequence of that I didn&#39;t<lb/> care for any <sic>employement</sic><lb/> which was offered to me<lb/> during the course of the<lb/> way to this country&#44; how&#45;<lb/>ever there was a very<lb/> <sic>conveniabe</sic> one. Three<lb/> years are now elapsed<lb/> since my landing here<lb/> and I am sorry to say<lb/></p> 
                
                <pb n="3"/> 
            <p>I am as far from my<lb/> aim as 3 years ago. In<lb/> all that time I couldn&#39;t<lb/> find an <sic>employement</sic> as<lb/> engineer or surveyor which<lb/> would secure me a certain<lb/> income and from which<lb/> I <sic>were</sic> able to gather some<lb/> means for my purpose&#91;.&#93;<lb/></p>
            <p>I was working already<lb/> as a common laborer but<lb/> even in that I was unlucky<lb/> so that I came to the con&#45;<lb/>clusion that with all my<lb/> <sic>sacrifying</sic> and striving<lb/> I wouldn&#39;t attain my<lb/> end&#91;.&#93;<lb/></p>
            <p>I <sic>heared</sic> that the <lb/> <sic>baron</sic> <sic>Hirsh</sic> is com&#45;<lb/>mencing the construc<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>tion of the Syrian and<lb/> <sic>Paletine</sic> Railway. I<lb/> want therefore go to <lb/> Paris and pray of you<lb/> very much to get for<lb/> me a good recommenda&#45;<lb/>tion to that man. I<lb/> understand French<lb/> as well as german&#44; en&#45;<lb/>glish and Russian<lb/> and &#94;think not I&#39;ll feel my<lb/> self very strange in Paris&#91;.&#93;<lb/></p>
            <p><sic>Sincerly</sic><lb/>
                Yours<lb/>
                N. I. Weinstein<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
